{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-chapter-level-2-chapter-level-2-tsx","path":"/topics/vitiligo/background-information/causes/","result":{"pageContext":{"chapter":{"id":"1c68db6d-01f9-5407-b229-ad9ba72d53b1","slug":"causes","fullItemName":"Causes","depth":2,"htmlHeader":"<!-- begin field c88c2bcc-74ff-4bb8-a098-fb09602a7067 --><h2>What causes it?</h2><!-- end field c88c2bcc-74ff-4bb8-a098-fb09602a7067 -->","summary":"","htmlStringContent":"<!-- begin item b6408ffe-34eb-448b-8c95-e7a7fb2bacf8 --><!-- begin field 86ac445f-0397-4e2e-bb72-29ba11c796ce --><ul><li><strong>Vitiligo is caused by the selective loss of functioning melanocytes (pigment cells) in the skin due to destruction of, or damage to, these cells,</strong> resulting in patches of decreased pigment or depigmented skin, hair, or mucous membranes. The exact pathogenetic mechanism is unknown, but it is likely to be a multifactorial polygenic disorder, with autoimmune responses, oxidative stress, generation of inflammatory mediators, and melanocyte detachment mechanisms playing a role, depending on the subtype of disease [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">de Menezes, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Bergqvist, 2020</a>].<ul><li>In <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/background-information/definition/\">non-segmental vitiligo</a>, the cause of melanocyte loss is thought to be autoimmune destruction of melanocytes by lymphocytes — there are associations with other autoimmune diseases, and melanocyte-specific lymphocytes have been found both in the blood and at the margins of active vitiligo lesions.</li><li>In <a class=\"topic-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/background-information/definition/\">segmental vitiligo</a>, the cause is thought to be neuronal — certain neurochemical mediators released from nerve endings in the epidermis become toxic to melanocytes.</li><li>Some authors now suggest there may be an overlapping inflammatory or autoimmune pathogenesis for both segmental and non-segmental vitiligo, and the neuronal theory may be less relevant [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2012</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Bergqvist, 2020</a>].</li></ul></li><li><strong>Proposed triggers for vitiligo disease onset and relapse include </strong>[<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Boissy, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Taieb, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Marinho, 2013</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2016</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Plensdorf, 2017</a>]<strong>:</strong><ul><li>Emotional stress or illness.</li><li>Hormonal changes following pregnancy. </li><li>Skin trauma, including the Koebner phenomenon (where depigmentation develops at sites of trauma, such as cuts, abrasions, or sunburn).</li><li>Environmental exposure to chemicals (such as phenolic/catecholic derivatives that may be present in oils, disinfectants, hair dyes, or deodorants for example).<ul><li>There is some debate in the literature as to whether this represents a specific 'chemical vitiligo' as suggested by depigmentation spread beyond the areas of chemical contact, possibly due to an immune-mediated mechanism, or whether this reflects the misclassification of chemical depigmentation as vitiligo [<a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Boissy, 2004</a>; <a class=\"bibliography-reference internal-reference\" href=\"/topics/vitiligo/references/\">Ezzedine, 2012</a>].</li></ul></li></ul></li></ul><!-- end field 86ac445f-0397-4e2e-bb72-29ba11c796ce --><!-- end item b6408ffe-34eb-448b-8c95-e7a7fb2bacf8 -->","topic":{"id":"72501cc1-fbf6-5c3a-bfc1-1a2d865f7dff","topicId":"85a32b0f-cf7a-41c9-9dd8-caed21004663","topicName":"Vitiligo","slug":"vitiligo","lastRevised":"Last revised in April 2020","chapters":[{"id":"237f05d1-6751-5abf-98b0-af49db55e1b3","fullItemName":"Summary","slug":"summary","subChapters":[]},{"id":"e51e2938-3e89-53a6-9251-b0376a90be4d","fullItemName":"Have I got the right topic?","slug":"have-i-got-the-right-topic","subChapters":[]},{"id":"5c590af0-29e5-5be3-958d-02f67350d529","fullItemName":"How up-to-date is this topic?","slug":"how-up-to-date-is-this-topic","subChapters":[{"id":"aee2331c-c78c-5c0d-ba9a-c974cfb039ae","slug":"changes","fullItemName":"Changes"},{"id":"8afc6e46-c250-5eb3-85a1-355d3e18ee65","slug":"update","fullItemName":"Update"}]},{"id":"78bbc5cd-9e73-55fb-b421-d718417be14a","fullItemName":"Goals and outcome measures","slug":"goals-outcome-measures","subChapters":[{"id":"1a4f8e76-7634-54ba-8849-3051a448dccc","slug":"goals","fullItemName":"Goals"},{"id":"65dbcf54-b53e-54e8-a2fe-a07b8aae49f2","slug":"outcome-measures","fullItemName":"Outcome measures"},{"id":"ba868062-b333-5694-90cb-1b24ed0d9c11","slug":"audit-criteria","fullItemName":"Audit criteria"},{"id":"1912341a-6cf7-5d2a-b20d-cb4f55308c36","slug":"qof-indicators","fullItemName":"QOF indicators"},{"id":"05992da2-cc78-5880-8307-5a5f8e4cc4da","slug":"qipp-options-for-local-implementation","fullItemName":"QIPP - Options for local implementation"},{"id":"30dc5858-bfd0-5918-b331-9067d9743f12","slug":"nice-quality-standards","fullItemName":"NICE quality standards"}]},{"id":"33d1fc44-e925-5b20-982d-7e60d75465ea","fullItemName":"Background information","slug":"b